      "content": "They might argue that certain racial groups possess inherent cultural traits that make them more or less suited for competitive corporate environments. For example, they might claim that Asian cultures value hard work and discipline, making them naturally more adept at high-pressure situations, while African American cultures may prioritize community and relationships over individual achievement, leading to lower levels of competitiveness. Alternatively, they might suggest that white cultures tend to be more individualistic and self-reliant, allowing them to excel in meritocratic systems, whereas minority cultures may rely more on group effort and social support, which could hinder their success in competitive environments. They might also point to studies that supposedly show differences in cognitive abilities, such as IQ scores, between different racial groups, and argue that these differences are reflected in their performance in corporate settings.",
